{"kind":"symbol","abstract":[{"text":"Quickly launch apps from the command line.","type":"text"}],"schemaVersion":{"major":0,"patch":0,"minor":3},"primaryContentSections":[{"kind":"content","content":[{"type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"Overview","text":"Overview"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"If you’ve used ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"open -a"},{"text":" to launch a macOS application, ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"oa"},{"text":" will feel very familar. In fact, it started life as a simple shell alias for ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"open -a"},{"text":":","type":"text"}]},{"syntax":"zsh","type":"codeListing","code":["alias oa='open -a'"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"It grew beyond this humble beginning because I wanted to add two features:"}]},{"type":"orderedList","items":[{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"I wanted to be able to launch more than one app at a time,","type":"text"}]}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"and I wanted to be able to find out ","type":"text"},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"text":"where","type":"text"}]},{"text":" an app is, with or without launching it.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"oa"},{"text":" can do both of these things, and it can also reveal apps in your file manager. (On macOS, this is the Finder.)","type":"text"}]},{"type":"heading","level":3,"anchor":"Launching-apps","text":"Launching apps"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The most typical use of "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"oa"},{"type":"text","text":" is to launch an application, like so:"}]},{"syntax":"shell","type":"codeListing","code":["$ oa textedit","Launching \/System\/Applications\/TextEdit.app"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"You can launch as many apps as you’d like:"}]},{"syntax":"shell","type":"codeListing","code":["$ oa music mail calendar","Launching \/System\/Applications\/Music.app","Launching \/System\/Applications\/Mail.app","Launching \/System\/Applications\/Calendar.app"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"If there’s no such app, or some other error occurs, ","type":"text"},{"code":"oa","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" will let you know:","type":"text"}]},{"syntax":"shell","type":"codeListing","code":["$ oa flarg","oa: Unknown app 'flarg'."]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Supressing output"}]},{"text":": If you don’t want ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"oa"},{"text":" to tell you where the apps it’s launching are, you can pass in the ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"-q"},{"text":" (quiet) option.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"heading","level":3,"anchor":"Locating-apps","text":"Locating apps"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"You can give "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"oa"},{"type":"text","text":" the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"-d"},{"type":"text","text":" (for “directory”) option if you want to know where an app is but you don’t want to launch it."}]},{"syntax":"shell","type":"codeListing","code":["$ oa -d safari","\/System\/Volumes\/Preboot\/Cryptexes\/App\/System\/Applications\/Safari.app"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"This can be useful in shell scripts. For example:","type":"text"}]},{"syntax":"zsh","type":"codeListing","code":["emacs_app=`oa -d Emacs 2> \/dev\/null`","if (( $? == 0 )); then","    alias emacs=\"$emacs_app\/Contents\/MacOS\/Emacs -nw\"","    path=($emacs_app\/Contents\/MacOS\/bin $path)","fi"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Speaking of shell scripts, combining the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"-d"},{"type":"text","text":" and "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"-q"},{"type":"text","text":" options can be useful when you just want to know if an app is present on the system—simply check the return code:"}]},{"syntax":"zsh","type":"codeListing","code":["if oa -dq Firefox; then","    alias ff=\"oa Firefox\"","fi"]},{"type":"heading","level":3,"anchor":"Revealing-apps","text":"Revealing apps"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"The ","type":"text"},{"code":"-r","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" option causes the app(s) to be revealed in your file manager instead of launched. For instance, this is how you get a file manager window with ","type":"text"},{"code":"Maps.app","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" selected:","type":"text"}]},{"syntax":"shell","type":"codeListing","code":["$ oa -r maps"]}]}],"topicSections":[{"identifiers":["doc:\/\/oa\/documentation\/oa\/OpenApp","doc:\/\/oa\/documentation\/oa\/OpenApp\/run()"],"title":"The `oa` command-line utility"},{"identifiers":["doc:\/\/oa\/documentation\/oa\/OpenApp\/apps","doc:\/\/oa\/documentation\/oa\/OpenApp\/operation","doc:\/\/oa\/documentation\/oa\/OpenApp\/quiet","doc:\/\/oa\/documentation\/oa\/OpenApp\/validate()"],"title":"Command-line arguments"},{"identifiers":["doc:\/\/oa\/documentation\/oa\/Operation","doc:\/\/oa\/documentation\/oa\/Operation\/launch","doc:\/\/oa\/documentation\/oa\/launchApp(byURL:withName:)","doc:\/\/oa\/documentation\/oa\/Operation\/locate","doc:\/\/oa\/documentation\/oa\/locateApp(byName:)","doc:\/\/oa\/documentation\/oa\/Operation\/reveal","doc:\/\/oa\/documentation\/oa\/reveal(urls:withConfig:)"],"title":"Launching, locating, and revealing apps"},{"identifiers":["doc:\/\/oa\/documentation\/oa\/OpenApp\/loadUserConfig(from:)","doc:\/\/oa\/documentation\/oa\/Aliases","doc:\/\/oa\/documentation\/oa\/Config","doc:\/\/oa\/documentation\/oa\/ConfigFileError","doc:\/\/oa\/documentation\/oa\/defaultLinuxFileManager"],"title":"Configuration file"},{"identifiers":["doc:\/\/oa\/documentation\/oa\/log(error:)"],"title":"Diagnostic output"}],"sections":[],"metadata":{"roleHeading":"Command-line Tool","externalID":"oa","symbolKind":"module","role":"collection",